{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17657056","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17657056"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:20+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-30T22:22:20+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19065"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"19065","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/19065"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.23,0.08,0.04,0.04,0.62]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11799"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82651"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"11799","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/11799"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19065"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67791"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"29"},{"type":"tags","id":"39"},{"type":"tags","id":"67"},{"type":"tags","id":"71"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4936"},{"type":"tags","id":"4940"},{"type":"tags","id":"4942"},{"type":"tags","id":"4947"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"27753"},{"type":"contributions","id":"28259"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82651","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/82651"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA research team is studying T cell responses in the laboratory. They observe that when T cells are stimulated through their T cell receptor alone, without additional signals, the cells become unresponsive to subsequent stimulation attempts.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following best describes the mechanism responsible for this T cell unresponsiveness?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Cytokine receptor downregulation","Memory T cell differentiation","Programmed cell death activation","Regulatory T cell conversion","T cell anergy induction"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThe observed unresponsiveness represents \u003Cstrong\u003ET cell anergy induction\u003C/strong\u003E. This occurs when T cells receive T cell receptor (TCR) signalling in the absence of CD28 co-stimulation. Anergy serves as a tolerance mechanism to prevent inappropriate T cell responses.\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cp\u003EThe incorrect options can be explained:\u003C/p\u003E        \u003Cul\u003E        \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EProgrammed cell death activation\u003C/strong\u003E - While some T cells may undergo apoptosis without proper stimulation, anergy is characterised by viable but unresponsive cells\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ERegulatory T cell conversion\u003C/strong\u003E - This requires specific cytokine signals including transforming growth factor beta, not just TCR stimulation alone\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMemory T cell differentiation\u003C/strong\u003E - Memory formation requires full activation with both TCR and co-stimulatory signals, plus appropriate cytokines\u003C/li\u003E                \u003Cli\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECytokine receptor downregulation\u003C/strong\u003E - While this may occur during T cell responses, it is not the primary mechanism of anergy\u003C/li\u003E    \u003C/ul\u003E        \u003Cp\u003ET cell anergy is crucial for maintaining self-tolerance by ensuring T cells only become fully activated when they receive appropriate signals from professional antigen-presenting cells. The absence of co-stimulation typically indicates that the antigen being presented is a self-antigen that should not trigger an immune response.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["T cells require both T cell receptor engagement with antigen-MHC and CD28 co-stimulation for proper activation.","Lack of co-stimulation leads to T cell anergy, a state of functional unresponsiveness.","T cell anergy is a crucial mechanism for maintaining self-tolerance and preventing autoimmune responses."],"references":["Chappert et al. Induction of T cell anergy: integration of environmental cues and infectious tolerance, Curr Opin Immunol. 2010, https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC2981408/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67791"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"19065"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"67791","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/67791"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-01-30T14:38:50+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-01-30T14:41:38+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"11799"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"82651"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"29","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/29"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udd2c","name":"Pathology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"4"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"39","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/39"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\udee1\ufe0f","name":"Immunology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:44+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"67","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/67"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Basic Science","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":n